Failing sui and the nearest agnate, the Twelve Tables had given the inheritance to the gentiles of the deceased3 ‘ si adgnatus nec escit, gentilis familiam nancitor.’ In iii. 17 Gaius alluades to a definition os gentiles in an earlier part of his work, which, however, has been lost, and the best account we have of them is that of Cicer0, Top. 6, cited by Mr. Poste in his note on the passage of Gaius referred to. Who they were precisely is of no practical importance, sor Gaius observes that even in his day the whole os the law relating to the subject was obsolete‚ ‘ totum gentilicium ius in desuetudinem abiisse! There was in fact no longer any civil law successor to an intestate in default of sui and agnates 3 the gap was filled by the praetor, who through the system of bonorum possessio substituted for the gentiles a third order of claimantS, ranking aster liberi and legitimi, viz. the deceased cognates or next of ltin, in their several degrees of proximity. Between two or more cog- nates related in the same degree the division was always in capita.
